1.Distinguish between the different sources of energy used for metabolism in muscle.
{{c1::Creatine phosphate}} can supply ATP in {{c2::skeletal muscle}} only.
2.Describe Creatine Phosphate pathways.
{{c1::Creatine kinase}} is an enzyme that transfers one phosphate from {{c2::creatine phosphate}} to ADP to yield {{c2::creatine}} and ATP.
"recycles muscle ADP"
2.Describe Creatine Phosphate pathways.
{{c1::Anaerobic}} glycolysis occurs in the {{c2::cytosol}} and converts {{c3::1 glucose}} molecule to {{c4::2 ATP, 2 Pyruvate, and NADH}}.
3.Describe the site and conversion of pyruvate to lactate to pyruvate.
The significance of {{c1::anaerobic glycolysis}} is to have {{c2::short term}} energy supply for skeletal muscle.
6.Describe the role of anaerobic, aerobic, oxidative phosphorylation, alpha, beta and gamma oxidation of fatty acids in muscle energy metabolism.

{{c6::Cori cycle}} refers to the metabolic pathway in which {{c1::lactate}} produced by {{c2::anaerobic glycolysis}} in the {{c3::muscles}} moves to the {{c4::liver}} and is converted to {{c5::pyruvate/glucose}}, which then returns to the {{c3::muscles}} and is cyclically metabolized back to {{c1::lactate}}.
3.Describe the site and conversion of pyruvate to lactate to pyruvate.
The significance of the {{c1::cori cycle}} is that it {{c2::prevents lactic acidosis}} in skeletal muscle.

Because it moves the lactic acid out of the muscle (lactic acid build-up can cause muscle fatigue).

The cycle is also important in producing ATP, an energy source, during muscle activity.
5. Describe the significance of Cori cycle and its role in lactic acidosis

The role of {{c1::lactate dehydrogenase::enzyme}} in muscle energy metabolism is to catalyze the conversion of {{c2::pyruvate to lactate}} in {{c3::muscle}} and {{c2::lactate to pyruvate}} in {{c3::liver}}.
Lactate, formed by the action of lactate dehydrogenase, is the final product of anaerobic glycolysis in eukaryotic cells.
4. What is the role of the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase in muscle energy metabolism.
The significance of the {{c1::alanine cycle}} is that it prevents a build up of {{c2::Nitrogen}} in the muscle in the form of {{c3::ammonium ions}}, which are toxic.
AKA Glucose-Alanine cycle or Cahill cycle
Alanine Cycle is not a learning objective but it was talked about in lecture and related to the cori cycle. (5. Describe the significance of Cori cycle and its role in lactic acidosis.)
{{c1::Alanine cycle}} is also known as {{c2::Cahill cycle}} or {{c2::glucose-alanine cycle}}.
Boards questions may refer to this cycle using any of its known names.
Alanine Cycle is not a learning objective but it was talked about in lecture and related to the cori cycle. (5. Describe the significance of Cori cycle and its role in lactic acidosis.)
Both the {{c1::Cori and Alanine}} cycles provides substrates for {{c2::gluconeogenesis}}.
Alanine Cycle is not a learning objective but it was talked about in lecture and related to the cori cycle. (5. Describe the significance of Cori cycle and its role in lactic acidosis.)
{{c1::Aerobic}} glycolysis occurs in {{c3::mitochondria}}  and produces {{c2::34 net}} ATP for energy used in walking or running.
The significance of Aerobic glycolysis is that produces a ton of ATP to keep muscles working. The limitation is oxygen.

The role of the {{c1::purine nucleotide}} cycle is to regulate {{c2::energy requirements for muscular contraction}}.

{{c1::Lipases}} are enzymes activated by {{c2::epinephrine and glucagon}} levels in the blood (or norepinephrine secreted by sympathetic nerves in adipose tissue).
Lipase levels increase by declining blood glucose and insulin levels in the blood (in between meals or when fasting).
